{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox scientist | name = James Allan Thomson | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 27 July 1881 | birth_place = [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1928|05|06|1881|07|27|df=y}} | death_place = [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]] | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | other_names = | residence = New Zealand | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = | patrons = | alma_mater = | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = | children = }}
'''James Allan Thomson''' (27 July 1881 &ndash; 6 May 1928) was a New Zealand geologist, scientific administrator and museum director.
He was born in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand, in 1881, where his father was a science teacher at [[Otago Boys' High School]]. He graduated from [[Otago University]] in 1904, the same year as [[Sir Peter Buck]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otago.ac.nz/library/exhibitions/rhodes_scholars/pdf/allan_thomson.pdf|format=PDF|title=Allan Thomson : New Zealand’s first Rhodes scholar|website=Otago.ac.nz|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> Selected as New Zealand's first [[Rhodes Scholar]], he studied geology, played [[Rugby union|rugby]], rowed and ran at [[ St John's College, Oxford]].
After doing geology in Australia, he was appointed palaeontologist with the [[New Zealand Geological Survey]] in 1911 and then succeeded [[Augustus Hamilton]] as director of the Dominion Museum (now [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Te Papa]]) in 1914. <ref name="DNZB Thomson">{{DNZB|title=James Allan Thomson|first= N. De B.|last= Hornibrook|id=3t33|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref>
He was accepted as a geologist on [[Robert Falcon Scott]]'s [[Terra Nova Expedition]] to [[Antarctica]], but he developed [[pulmonary tuberculosis]] and was forced to withdraw. The [[tuberculosis]] continued to trouble him and his health declined.<ref name="DNZB Thomson"/>
He was president of the [[Royal Society of New Zealand]] for a short time before his death in 1928; he was preceded by [[ Bernard Cracroft Aston]], who also stepped in after his death until the appointment of [[ Clinton Coleridge Farr]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org.nz/who-we-are/our-people/our-council/presidents/|title=Royal Society Te Apārangi - Presidents|website=Royalsociety.org.nz|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>
His daughter [[Margaret Thomson|Margaret]] became a noted film director.<ref name=nzonscreen>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzonscreen.com/person/margaret-thomson/biography|title=Margaret Thomson - NZ On Screen|website=Nzonscreen.com|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>
==Selected works== *''Brachiopod morphology and genera: recent and tertiary '' [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Dominion Museum]], 1927. Wellington New Zealand.
