! #111
! 4.27<ref name="season12-13">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/05/29/complete-list-of-2012-13-season-tv-show-viewership-sunday-night-football-tops-followed-by-ncis-the-big-bang-theory-ncis-los-angeles/184781/ |title=Complete List Of 2012-13 Season TV Show Viewership: 'Sunday Night Football' Tops, Followed By 'NCIS,' 'The Big Bang Theory' & 'NCIS: Los Angeles' |work=TV by the Numbers |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=May 29, 2013 |accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref>
|}
''Fringe'' premiered in the [[2008–09 United States network television schedule|2008 United States television season]] at a regular timeslot of 9:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern on Tuesdays.  During Season 1, ''Fringe'' was part of a Fox initiative known as "Remote-Free TV". Episodes of ''Fringe'' were longer than standard dramas on current network television. The show ran with half the commercials, adding about six minutes to the show's runtime.<ref name="Remote Free">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117985767?refCatId=1300 |title=New Fox dramas to limit commercials |accessdate=2008-05-18 |last=Schneider |first=Michael |date=2008-05-15 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> When the show went to a commercial, a short bumper aired informing the viewer of roughly how much time commercials would consume before the program resumed. The pilot episode was leaked via [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]], three months before the series premiere; similar to leaked fellow Fox series ''[[Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2008/06/fringe-pilot-le/ |title=Fringe Pilot Leaks Online Three Months Before Premiere |accessdate=2008-09-16 |last=Jenna |first=Wortham |date=2008-06-17 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref> The series was renewed for a second season on May 4, 2009,<ref>{{cite web |last=Seidman |first=Robert |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2009/05/04/fox-renews-fringe/17977 |title=FOX renews Fringe for a full second season |publisher=TV by the Numbers |date=2009-05-04 |accessdate=2010-10-12}}</ref> and moved to 9:00&nbsp;p.m. on Thursday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/983/983821p1.html |title=Fringe Moves to Risky Timeslot; Dollhouse Stays Put on Fridays |publisher=IGN |first=Eric |last=Goldman |date=2009-05-18 |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref>

It was renewed for a third season on March 6, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/03/06/exclusive-fringe-picked-up-for-a-third-season/ |title=Exclusive: Fringe picked up for a third season |first=Lynette |last=Rice |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=2011-05-23 |date=2011-05-06}}</ref> As part of a reorganization of its [[2010–2011 United States network television schedule|2010 midseason]] line up to capture more market for ''[[American Idol]]'', the Fox network shifted ''Fringe'' to 9:00&nbsp;p.m. on Fridays.  This timeslot, commonly considered the "[[Friday night death slot]]" for several previous Fox shows due to cancellation shortly following the move to that slot, left critics considering the show's fate.  While ''The X-Files'' originally premiered during this slot and would continue to be a highly successful series, critics were unsure if ''Fringe'' could duplicate this performance.  In this slot, the show competed with ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]'', a series that attracts similar types of viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/113/1135956p1.html |title=Fringe's Scary New Timeslot |first=Eric |last=Goldman |date=2010-11-19 |accessdate=2010-11-19 |publisher=IGN}}</ref> Fox's Entertainment President [[Kevin Reilly (executive)|Kevin Reilly]], in response to these concerns, stated that 45% of ''Fringe''{{'}}s viewership is from [[time shifting]] recording through digital video receivers, and does not expect the viewership numbers to change significantly with the change to Friday. Reilly further postulated that "If it does anywhere near what it did on Thursdays, we can glue that show to the schedule because it can be a big win for us".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/11/22/fox-execs-on-american-idol-fringe-moves-its-the-right-moment/ |title=Fox execs on 'American Idol,' 'Fringe' moves: 'It's the right moment' |first=Lynette |last=Rice |date=2010-11-22 |accessdate=2010-11-30 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Further promoted by the critical reaction to the rescheduling, the Fox network created a self-deprecating promotional advertisement acknowledging the reputation of the time slot, including quotes from other media outlets concerned about the move, but asserted that the move would "re-animate" the show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2010/12/fringe_friday_time_slot.html |title=Fox Markets Fringe With New 'Friday Death Slot' Ad |first=Kyle |last=Buchaan |date=2010-12-14 |accessdate=2010-12-16 |work=[[New York Magazine]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/12/16/fringe-exclusive-friday-promo-deathslot/ |title='Fringe' exclusive: Fox execs on its 'deathslot'-spoofing promo and plans to attract new viewers |first=Jeff |last=Jensen |date=2010-12-16 |accessdate=2010-12-16 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> The network also created a music video, set to "[[Echoes (Klaxons song)|Echoes]]" by the band [[Klaxons]] as a means of summarizing the third season to date prior to the first Friday broadcast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/18/exclusive-fringe-music-video-echoes/ |title=Watch the 'Fringe' music video 'Echoes' -- EXCLUSIVE |first=Jeff |last=Jensen |date=2011-01-18 |accessdate=2011-01-18 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Joshua Jackson, who plays Peter Bishop on the show, cautioned that time-shifted viewership may not be enough to save the show: "It's not that not enough people are watching ''Fringe'', it's that not enough people are watching ''Fringe'' during the hour that it's on the air, which is key for the network."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-01-21/entertainment/27096167_1_fbi-agent-olivia-dunham-fringe-show |title=Joshua Jackson returns with new season of 'Fringe' hoping to soldify show's uncertain future |first=Ethan |last=Sacks |date=2011-01-21 |accessdate=2011-01-21 |work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref>

Producers Pinkner and Wyman also were excited about the move to Fridays, considering the slot as "open territory that can be conquered" and that they "can actually deliver like ''The X-Files'' did".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blastr.com/2010/12/fringe-producers-why-the.php |title=Fringe producers: Why our move to Fridays is a GOOD thing |publisher=[[Blastr]] |first=Kathie |last=Huddleson |date=2010-12-02 |accessdate=2011-01-13}}</ref> Series creator Abrams was less optimistic of the move to Friday nights, aware that the show's likelihood to be renewed for a fourth season would be highly dependent on the number of niche viewers that continue to watch the show.<ref name="abrams fridaynight">{{cite web |url=http://blastr.com/2011/01/jj-abrams-reaction-to-fox.php |title=J.J. Abrams' reaction to Fox moving Fringe to Fridays: 'Sh*t!' |publisher=[[Blastr]] |date=2011-01-12 |accessdate=2012-01-13 |first=Fred |last=Topel}}</ref> Abrams did affirm that moving to Friday nights allows them to take more creative freedoms to maintain viewership in the new timeslot, but feels that if the show was not renewed for another season, they would be "hard pressed" to resolve the story by the end of the third season.<ref name="abrams fridaynight"/>

The show's first episode at the Friday 9:00&nbsp;p.m. timeslot ("[[The Firefly (Fringe)|The Firefly]]") scored a 1.9 in the key 18–49 demographic which was an increase of 12% over its last Thursday-aired episode ("Marionette") which scored a 1.7,<ref>{{cite web |first=Bill |last=Gorman |date=January 22, 2011 |work=TV by the Numbers |title=Updated TV Ratings Friday: 'Fringe' Premieres Up, 'Medium' Series Finale Rises, 'Kitchen Nightmares' Starts Well |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/01/22/tv-ratings-friday-fringe-premieres-up/79750 |accessdate=2011-04-08}}</ref> and maintained similar numbers in the second week for "[[Reciprocity (Fringe)|Reciprocity]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/01/29/updated-tv-ratings-friday-fringe-holds-steady-kitchen-nightmares-down/80704 |title=Updated TV Ratings Friday: 'Fringe' Holds Steady, 'Kitchen Nightmares' Down |first=Robert |last=Seidman |date=2011-01-29 |accessdate=2011-01-29 |publisher=TV by the Numbers}}</ref> Though viewership slipped in further weeks, the show was renewed for a fourth season in March 2011. The move was unexpected based on these ratings, given the past performance of shows with similar viewership numbers in the Friday night slot, but several critics attribute it to the strong fanbase that the show has garnered, which contributes in part to consistently higher time-shifted viewership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-03-28/entertainment/fringe.ratings.go_1_science-fiction-fans-licorice-low-ratings?_s=PM:SHOWBIZ |title='Fringe' renewed: Can fan passion trump |first=Henry |last=Hanks |date=2011-03-28 |accessdate=2011-03-30 |publisher=CNN |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423124637/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-03-28/entertainment/fringe.ratings.go_1_science-fiction-fans-licorice-low-ratings?_s=PM%3ASHOWBIZ |archivedate=2011-04-23 |df=}}</ref> Fox's Reilly stated that:

{{quote|''Fringe'' has truly hit a creative stride and has distinguished itself as one of television's most original programs. The series' ingenious producers, amazingly talented cast and crew, as well as some of the most passionate and loyal fans on the planet, made this fourth-season pickup possible. When we moved the show to Fridays, we asked the fans to follow and they did. We're thrilled to bring it back for another full season and keep it part of the Fox family.|Kevin Reilly, President of Fox Entertainment<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2011/03/24/breaking-fox-renews-fringe/ |title=Breaking: Fox Renews Fringe for Season 4! |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |publisher=[[TVLine.com]] |date=2011-03-25 |accessdate=2011-03-25}}</ref>}}

Reilly further added that the renewal was also prompted by the high risk of trying to replace ''Fringe'' with another show with unknown viewership metrics; he commented that they "have a far better shot of sticking with a show that has an audience that [they] think [they] can grow".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2011-04-01-SOS01_CV_N.htm |title=Save our shows! TV series fight for survival |first=Gary |last=Levin |date=2011-04-01 |accessdate=2011-04-01 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> Prior to the onset of the fourth season, Reilly reiterated that they do not expect any significant growth in ''Fringe''{{'}}s viewership within that season: "It's a pretty complex show. If ''Fringe'' can do exactly what ''Fringe'' did last year, we're going to be very happy. They're right in the pocket creatively once again."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/08/05/fox-doesnt-expect-fringe-to-grow-in-ratings/ |title=Fox doesn't expect 'Fringe' to grow in ratings |first=James |last=Hibbart |date=2011-08-05 |accessdate=2011-08-06 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Wyman stated in an interview with ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' that the Fox network had been "supportive throughout this process", and though the show's viewership "wasn't exactly what they would've hoped for", aspects such as a loyal fan base and supportive critics were enough to take the show forward for another season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fringe-executive-producer-calls-season-171598 |title='Fringe' Executive Producer Calls Season 4 Renewal 'Gutsy' |first=Philiana |last=Ng |date=2011-03-25 |accessdate=2011-03-25 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Pinkner commented that "there were no creative conditions" on the show's renewal, nor any cuts in the show's budget, though was unsure if the show will be moved to a different time slot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/04/15/fringe-leonard-nimoy-renewal/ |title='Fringe' scoop: More on Leonard Nimoy's 'animated' return. Plus: The producers on the show's 'anti-climactic' renewal |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=2011-04-15 |accessdate=2011-04-15 |first=Jeff |last=Jansen}}</ref> Noble, at the 2011 Comic-Con ''Fringe'' panel, reiterated that the fans were responsible for the livelihood of the show, stated, "Seriously, without your efforts, your rabid support, we wouldn't be here right now. You are the best fans that ever existed".<ref name="ew 2011sdcc">{{cite news |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/07/23/fringe-panel/?ew_packageID=20399642 |title='Fringe' at Comic-Con: Is Jeff Probst or Zach Quinto replacing Josh Jackson? -- VIDEO |first=Lynette |last=Rice |date=2011-07-24 |accessdate=2011-07-25 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> The fourth season premiered on September 23, 2011.<ref>{{cite press |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2011/06/23/fox-announces-fall-premiere-dates-for-the-2011-2012-season-2112/20110623fox01/ |title=FOX Announces Fall Premiere Dates for the 2011-2012 Season |publisher=Fox |accessdate=2011-06-23 |date=2011-06-23}}</ref>

Before the renewal of the fifth season, Abrams stated some skepticism for a renewal opportunity, but hoped that if it was cancelled, that it may be picked up by another network. On the other hand, Abrams considered that if Fox did pick up the show for a fifth season, "the next year would be the great ending for the show".<ref name="ign 5th season">{{Cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/121/1216068p1.html |title=Fringe: J.J. Abrams, FOX on a Potential Season 5 |first=Eric |last=Goldman |date=2012-01-08 |accessdate=2012-01-12 |publisher=[[IGN]]}}</ref> Similarly, Fox's Reilly remained cautious about a renewal, noting that while the show is one of the top shows in the Friday night slot, "it's an expensive show. We lose a lot of money on the show."<ref name="ign 5th season"/> Reilly further reiterated the dedication of the fans of the show for helping it to its fourth season and continued success.<ref name="ign 5th season"/> When asked about whether the writers would have enough notice to write the fourth-season finale as a series finale if necessary, Reilly stated, "That's a [[Peter Roth (executive)|Peter Roth]] issue" (chief executive of [[Warner Bros. Television]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/01/09/joshua-jackson-fringe-warning/ |title=Joshua Jackson reacts to Fox's 'Fringe' warning |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2012-01-19}}</ref> To which Roth responded, "We have no plans to give viewers closure this season because we expect the series to continue".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theclicker.today.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/01/09/10072682-fox-chief-warns-that-the-future-of-fringe-is-in-doubt |title=FOX chief warns that the future of 'Fringe' is in doubt |work=The Clicker |first=Susan |last=Young |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2012-01-19}}</ref> In late January 2012, Fox and Warner Bros. Television were working on negotiating a lower licensing cost for the show to allow a fifth season to occur; this would not only help Fox reduce its losses on the show, but would also bring the total number of episodes above 100, giving Warner Bros. a better opportunity to syndicate reruns of the show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2012/01/22/fringe-season-5-renewal-cancellation/ |title=Fringe Update: Season 5 Discussions Underway, J.J. Abrams 'Hopeful' Show Will Be Back |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=2012-01-23 |accessdate=2012-01-23 |publisher=[[TV Line]]}}</ref> Before the announcement of the fifth season, Wyman and Pinkner stated that they would have created a series finale for the end of the fourth season should the show be cancelled; Wyman stated "We want to take care of the fans. We want them to see where it would have gone, but we also know the show has been a commitment and we want everyone to be satisfied with it."<ref name="nydn s5 finale">{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-02-23/news/31093068_1_fringe-jeff-pinkner-sci-fi-show |title='Fringe' hopes for a future, but is ready for an end |first=David |last=Hickley |date=2012-02-23 |accessdate=2012-03-02 |work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref>

The show was officially renewed for a fifth and final season for the 2012–2013 television season, consisting of a shortened set of 13 episodes, on April 26, 2012, with its premiere on September 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Hibberd |work=Entertainment Weekly |title=Official: 'Fringe' renewed for final season! |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/04/26/fringe-final-season/ |accessdate=2012-04-26 |date=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/07/01/comic-con-exclusive-sneak-peek-at-fringe-poster-and-observageddon/ |title=Comic-Con Exclusive: Sneak peek at 'Fringe' poster ... and Observageddon! |work=Entertainment Weekly |last=Jensen |first=Jeff |date=2012-07-01 |accessdate=2010-08-08}}</ref> Reilly, in announcing the renewal, stated that "''Fringe'' is a remarkably creative series that has set the bar as one of television's most imaginative dramas. Bringing it back for a final 13 allows us to provide the climactic conclusion that its passionate and loyal fans deserve".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1683991/fringe-renewed-season-five.jhtml |title='Fringe' Renewed For Fifth And Final Season |first=Kara |last=Warner |date=2012-04-26 |accessdate=2012-04-26 |publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref> The writing team crafted an idea for a cohesive story-driven set of thirteen episodes as a means to complete the series, and to "honor the audience that had served us so well was to say a proper farewell", according to Roth.<ref name="tvguide oralhistory pt4">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Fringe-Series-Finale-Oral-History-Abrams-Jackson-Torv-Noble-1059246.aspx |title=Fringe Oral History: The Road to the Series Finale |first=Natalie |last=Abrams |date=2013-01-17 |accessdate=2013-01-26 |work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> Noble called it "the season for the fans", with the story revisiting many of the elements from the show's past.<ref name="tvguide oralhistory pt4"/>

===Awards and nominations===
{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Fringe}}
''Fringe'' and its cast and crew have been nominated and won several awards including [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmys]], [[Saturn Award]]s, [[Motion Picture Sound Editors|Golden Reel Awards]], [[Satellite Award]]s, and [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s.

